Third-party components
======================

libsepol 3.10 (SELinux userspace), LGPL-2.1, statically linked into the
DEFAULT build.

  - As of #124 the `authoritative-categorizer` feature is DEFAULT-ON, so a
    plain `cargo build` / the shipped release binary statically links
    libsepol 3.10 and carries the LGPL-2.1 obligation. (A
    `cargo build --no-default-features` build links NO libsepol and is the
    clean Apache-2.0-only build with no LGPL obligation -- see "Licensing
    posture" below.)
  - Built from the libsepol 3.10 source vendored in-tree at
    crates/rulesteward-selinux-sys/vendor/libsepol/ and statically linked
    (the build recipe + version pin are in that directory's README.txt; the
    build is driven by crates/rulesteward-selinux-sys/build.rs).
  - License: GNU Lesser General Public License, version 2.1. The full text is
    in LICENSES/LGPL-2.1.txt and in vendor/libsepol/LICENSE. The complete,
    corresponding libsepol source is included in this repository under
    crates/rulesteward-selinux-sys/vendor/libsepol/ (upstream:
    https://github.com/SELinuxProject/selinux, release 3.10), satisfying the
    LGPL-2.1 source-availability requirement for the shipped binary.

The single-static-binary distribution model is preserved: libsepol is linked
into the default binary as a static archive (LGPL-2.1 permits static linking
with this notice and the accompanying license text, given the complete
corresponding source and the ability to relink -- both satisfied here).

Licensing posture
=================

The DEFAULT build (Apache-2.0 engine + statically-linked LGPL-2.1 libsepol):

  - The RuleSteward engine remains Apache-2.0 (see LICENSE).
  - libsepol 3.10 (LGPL-2.1) is statically linked. The LGPL-2.1 full text is
    in LICENSES/LGPL-2.1.txt; the complete corresponding source is vendored
    in-tree at crates/rulesteward-selinux-sys/vendor/libsepol/.

The clean Apache-2.0-only build:

  - `cargo build --no-default-features` (equivalently, building
    rulesteward-cli with its default feature off) links NO libsepol and
    carries no LGPL obligation. This is the build for downstreams that want
    an Apache-2.0-only artifact.

Why static linking of an LGPL-2.1 library is permitted here (LGPL-2.1 section 6):
an open-source application may distribute a binary that statically links an
LGPL-2.1 library when (a) the complete corresponding source of the library is
provided -- it is vendored in-tree at
crates/rulesteward-selinux-sys/vendor/libsepol/ and travels with the source
release; (b) relinking the application against a modified library is possible
-- the static archive is reproducibly built from that vendored source via
crates/rulesteward-selinux-sys/build.rs, so a recipient can rebuild libsepol
and relink; and (c) the LGPL-2.1 license text + this notice ship with the
binary -- LICENSES/LGPL-2.1.txt and this NOTICE are attached to every release
and installed by the RPM. All three conditions are satisfied.
